---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "How much internet speed do I need for online gaming?",
    a: "For most online games, you need far less download speed than you think — 15-25 Mbps is enough for a smooth experience in games like Valorant, CS2, Fortnite, and Apex Legends. What actually matters for gaming is ping (latency) and packet loss. A 500 Mbps connection with 80ms ping will feel worse than a 25 Mbps connection with 15ms ping. Your download speed matters more for game updates, patches, and downloading new titles, where 50-100+ Mbps makes a real difference. Upload speed matters if you stream — aim for at least 10 Mbps for 1080p streaming and 20+ Mbps for 4K."
  },
  {
    q: "What is a good ping for gaming?",
    a: "Under 20ms is excellent and gives you a competitive edge in fast-paced shooters like Valorant and CS2. 20-50ms is good and perfectly playable for most games. 50-100ms is acceptable for casual games, MMOs, and RPGs but you'll notice delays in FPS games. Over 100ms creates noticeable lag — rubber-banding, hit registration issues, and delayed actions. For competitive gaming, always connect to the nearest server region and use a wired Ethernet connection. Your ping is primarily determined by your physical distance to the game server and the quality of your ISP's routing, not your download speed."
  },
  {
    q: "Is wired Ethernet really that much better than WiFi for gaming?",
    a: "Yes — the difference is significant. Wired Ethernet provides consistent latency (typically 1-3ms to your router) with zero packet loss, while WiFi adds 2-15ms of variable latency and is susceptible to interference from walls, other devices, and neighboring networks. WiFi 6 (802.11ax) has improved things but still can't match wired for consistency. The biggest issue isn't average speed — it's jitter (variation in latency). WiFi jitter causes micro-stutters and rubber-banding even on fast connections. If you can't run an Ethernet cable, use a powerline adapter or MoCA adapter as a middle ground. WiFi 6E on 6GHz is the best wireless option if wired isn't possible."
  },
  {
    q: "Does a faster internet plan reduce my ping?",
    a: "No — upgrading from 100 Mbps to 1 Gbps will not lower your ping. Ping is determined by the physical distance to the server, the number of network hops between you and the server, and your ISP's routing quality. What a faster plan does help with is preventing congestion on your home network. If you're gaming on a 50 Mbps connection while someone else streams 4K Netflix and another person downloads a game, your ping will spike because the router is saturated. A faster plan gives more headroom so concurrent activities don't choke your gaming traffic. You can also use QoS (Quality of Service) settings on your router to prioritize gaming packets regardless of plan speed."
  },
  {
    q: "What is packet loss and how does it affect gaming?",
    a: "Packet loss is when data packets traveling between your PC and the game server are dropped and never arrive. Even 1% packet loss causes noticeable issues: rubber-banding, teleporting players, hit registration failures, and abilities not activating. At 2-3%, most competitive games become unplayable. Packet loss can be caused by WiFi interference, damaged Ethernet cables, ISP routing issues, congested servers, or overloaded routers. To test, run 'ping -n 100 8.8.8.8' on Windows or 'ping -c 100 8.8.8.8' on Mac/Linux and check the loss percentage. If you're getting packet loss on a wired connection, contact your ISP — it's likely a routing or infrastructure issue on their end."
  },
  {
    q: "Can I stream on Twitch and game at the same time?",
    a: "Yes, but your upload speed is critical. Streaming at 1080p 60fps to Twitch requires about 6-8 Mbps upload (Twitch recommends 6000 Kbps bitrate). At 720p 60fps, you need about 4-5 Mbps. Add your game's upload requirement (1-3 Mbps) and some headroom, and you need at least 10-15 Mbps upload for comfortable simultaneous gaming and streaming. Most cable internet plans have asymmetric speeds — you might have 300 Mbps down but only 10 Mbps up. Fiber plans typically offer symmetric speeds (300/300 or 1000/1000), making them ideal for streamers. Also use NVENC (NVIDIA) or VCE (AMD) hardware encoding to offload the stream from your CPU."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I lower my ping without changing ISP?",
    a: "Several things can help: 1) Use a wired Ethernet connection — this alone can drop ping by 5-15ms. 2) Change your DNS to Cloudflare (1.1.1.1) or Google (8.8.8.8) — faster DNS resolution means quicker initial connections. 3) Close background apps and downloads — Windows updates, cloud sync, and browser tabs consume bandwidth. 4) Enable QoS on your router and prioritize your gaming device. 5) Select the nearest game server region. 6) Restart your router/modem monthly to clear routing tables. 7) Consider a gaming VPN like ExitLag or WTFast if your ISP has poor routing to game servers — these can sometimes reduce ping by routing traffic more directly."
  },
  {
    q: "What internet speed do I need for cloud gaming (GeForce NOW, Xbox Cloud)?",
    a: "Cloud gaming has the highest bandwidth requirements of any gaming activity because you're streaming video in real-time. NVIDIA GeForce NOW requires 15 Mbps minimum for 720p, 25 Mbps for 1080p 60fps, and 40 Mbps for 4K. Xbox Cloud Gaming recommends 20 Mbps minimum. For a good experience, aim for at least 35-50 Mbps dedicated to cloud gaming with ping under 40ms to the nearest data center. Unlike traditional gaming where only small packets are sent, cloud gaming streams full video — so download speed actually matters here. Packet loss and jitter are even more devastating for cloud gaming than traditional gaming since they cause visible video artifacts and input lag spikes."
  }
];

