      <!-- ISP & Network Optimization Tips -->
      <h2>Network Optimization Tips</h2>

      <h3>Wired vs WiFi</h3>
      <p>A wired Ethernet connection is the single biggest improvement you can make for gaming network quality. Here's what to know:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ethernet (Cat 5e/6):</strong> Consistent 1-3ms latency to router, zero packet loss, no interference. Use Cat 6 for runs over 50 feet or if you have gigabit internet. Cat 5e works fine for most setups.</li>
        <li><strong>WiFi 6 (802.11ax):</strong> Good average speeds but variable latency (5-20ms jitter). Performance degrades through walls and with distance. Use 5GHz band for gaming — it's faster but shorter range than 2.4GHz.</li>
        <li><strong>WiFi 6E (6GHz):</strong> The best wireless option — less interference due to the new 6GHz band. Still adds 3-8ms vs wired but much more consistent than WiFi 5 or 6.</li>
        <li><strong>Powerline adapters:</strong> Use your home's electrical wiring to carry Ethernet. Performance varies by wiring quality — typically 50-200 Mbps with latency close to wired. A good middle ground if you can't run a cable.</li>
        <li><strong>MoCA adapters:</strong> Use coaxial cable (cable TV wiring) for Ethernet. More reliable than powerline — typically 500+ Mbps with near-wired latency. The best alternative if running Ethernet isn't possible.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Router QoS Settings</h3>
      <p>Quality of Service (QoS) tells your router to prioritize gaming traffic over other activities on your network:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>SQM (Smart Queue Management):</strong> The gold standard — available on routers with OpenWrt or custom firmware. SQM (fq_codel or CAKE) eliminates bufferbloat and keeps ping low even under heavy network load.</li>
        <li><strong>Device Priority:</strong> Most modern routers let you set your gaming PC or console as a high-priority device. This ensures gaming packets go first when the network is congested.</li>
        <li><strong>Application Priority:</strong> Some routers can identify game traffic by port or protocol and prioritize it. Enable "Gaming Mode" if your router has it.</li>
        <li><strong>Bandwidth Limits:</strong> Set download/upload limits for other devices (e.g., cap streaming devices to 25 Mbps) to reserve bandwidth for gaming.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>DNS Optimization</h3>
      <p>Your DNS server resolves domain names to IP addresses. Faster DNS means quicker initial connections to game servers and shorter loading times:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cloudflare DNS (1.1.1.1):</strong> Fastest public DNS with a focus on privacy. Secondary: 1.0.0.1</li>
        <li><strong>Google DNS (8.8.8.8):</strong> Extremely reliable with global coverage. Secondary: 8.8.4.4</li>
        <li><strong>Quad9 (9.9.9.9):</strong> Blocks known malicious domains automatically. Good for security-minded users.</li>
        <li><strong>How to change:</strong> Set DNS on your router (affects all devices) or on your PC in Network Settings → IPv4 → DNS Server. Router-level is preferred so all devices benefit.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Router Placement</h3>
      <p>If you must use WiFi, router placement significantly impacts signal quality:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Central location:</strong> Place the router in the center of your home, elevated (on a shelf or mounted on a wall) for best coverage.</li>
        <li><strong>Away from interference:</strong> Keep the router away from microwaves, baby monitors, Bluetooth devices, and thick walls/metal surfaces.</li>
        <li><strong>Antenna orientation:</strong> If your router has external antennas, position them at different angles (one vertical, one at 45°) for better multi-floor coverage.</li>
        <li><strong>Mesh systems:</strong> For large homes, a mesh WiFi system (like a 3-node setup) provides better coverage than a single powerful router. Place a mesh node near your gaming setup.</li>
      </ul>

